OpenShift Pod — URL Connectivity Check
Target: https://eccenterprisegis.enp.aramco.com.sa/arcgis  |  Container: UBI8 / nginx-122

Ops Guide
1
Get the Pod Name
List all pods in your namespace and copy the running pod name.

oc get pods -n <your-namespace>
ℹ️
Replace <your-namespace> with the actual OpenShift project name (e.g. agwa-prod). Look for a pod with Running status.
2
Test HTTPS Connectivity via curl
Exec into the pod and run curl against the target URL with verbose output and a timeout.

oc exec -n <your-namespace> <pod-name> -- \
  curl -v --max-time 10 \
  https://eccenterprisegis.enp.aramco.com.sa/arcgis
3
Fallback — Use wget if curl is Unavailable
Some minimal builds strip curl. Use wget as an alternative.

oc exec -n <your-namespace> <pod-name> -- \
  wget -O- --timeout=10 \
  https://eccenterprisegis.enp.aramco.com.sa/arcgis
4
DNS Resolution Check
Verify the hostname resolves from inside the pod. A timeout here means DNS is broken, not the host itself.

oc exec -n <your-namespace> <pod-name> -- \
  nslookup eccenterprisegis.enp.aramco.com.sa
5
Interpret the curl Output
Diagnostic table — match your output to the row below:

curl Output	Status	Meaning & Next Action
Connected to … + HTTP 2xx/3xx	PASS	Pod reaches the host. Network is fine.
Could not resolve host	DNS FAIL	DNS broken inside the pod. Check CoreDNS config or add a custom DNS entry.
Connection refused	PORT BLOCKED	Host is reachable but port 443 is closed on the remote side.
Connection timed out	EGRESS BLOCKED	EgressNetworkPolicy or corporate firewall is dropping the traffic.
SSL certificate problem	TLS ISSUE	Host reachable but cert is self-signed or untrusted. Add -k flag to skip (test only).
HTTP 401 / 403	REACHABLE	Network is fine — auth token or permissions issue on the server side.
6
Check OpenShift Network Policies (if Step 2 times out)
Run these from your local terminal (not inside the pod) to inspect egress rules.

# Check EgressNetworkPolicy (older OpenShift)
oc get egressnetworkpolicy -n <your-namespace>

# Check standard NetworkPolicy
oc get networkpolicy -n <your-namespace>

# Check EgressFirewall (OpenShift 4.x)
oc get egressfirewall -n <your-namespace>
⚠️
If any egress rule exists that does not explicitly Allow the IP range of eccenterprisegis.enp.aramco.com.sa, traffic will be silently dropped.
7
Corporate Proxy (if required)
If the cluster routes egress through a corporate proxy, the pod environment must have the proxy vars set.

# Check if proxy env vars exist in the pod
oc exec -n <your-namespace> <pod-name> -- env | grep -i proxy

# Test curl through a proxy explicitly
oc exec -n <your-namespace> <pod-name> -- \
  curl -v --proxy http://<proxy-host>:<port> \
  https://eccenterprisegis.enp.aramco.com.sa/arcgis
✅
If the proxy test succeeds but the direct test fails, add HTTP_PROXY / HTTPS_PROXY / NO_PROXY env vars to your OpenShift Deployment or DeploymentConfig.
